The new patients were found in counties including Nairobi (142), Kiambu (16) and (Nakuru) 14,. 

Machakos and Uasin Gishu followed with nine new cases each and then came Laikipia with six, Mombasa five, Meru and Nyeri three each, Bomet, Elgeyo Marakwet, Garissa, Kajiado, Kilifi, Kwale and Turkana two each. 

Narok, Nyamira, Trans Nzoia, Kakamega and Kericho each recorded just one new case. 

Six more deaths 

CS Kagwe further announced that another six patients had succumbed to the virus, raising the death toll in Kenya to 1,813. 






He also reported that 75 more patients had recovered, 49 of them under the home-based care programme and 26 in hospital, raising the total to 85,532. 

As of Friday, 333 patients had been admitted at health facilities countywide while 1,150 were being treated at home. 

Forty nine of those admitted were in intensive care units (ICU), 21 of them on ventilatory support, 23 on supplemental oxygen and five under observation. 

Another nine patients were separately on supplementary oxygen, five of them in general wards. 

